{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01LvTBmWJYLXVWtWGGaPFijy","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→Feature: Requirements Drafting and Project Seed Handoff\n     2→  The `requirements` command family drives idea-to-seed workflows. Draft mode\n     3→  generates clarifying questions and waits for user answers before proceeding.\n     4→  Quick mode skips questions entirely. Both modes pass through a draft, review,\n     5→  and seed generation pipeline, persisting validated payloads, artifacts, and\n     6→  seed files at durable boundaries.\n     7→\n     8→  # RD-001\n     9→  Scenario: Draft mode generates clarifying questions\n    10→    Given a workspace with an initialized project\n    11→    When the user runs \"requirements draft --idea 'Build a REST API'\"\n    12→    Then a requirements run is created in draft mode\n    13→    And clarifying questions are generated\n    14→    And the run transitions to \"awaiting_answers\" status\n    15→    And an answers.toml template is written to the run directory\n    16→\n    17→  # RD-002\n    18→  Scenario: Draft mode with empty questions skips to completion\n    19→    Given a workspace with an initialized project\n    20→    When the user runs \"requirements draft --idea 'Simple change'\"\n    21→    And the backend returns an empty question set\n    22→    Then the run continues directly through draft, review, and seed\n    23→    And the run status is \"completed\"\n    24→\n    25→  # RD-003\n    26→  Scenario: Quick mode skips questions entirely\n    27→    Given a workspace with an initialized project\n    28→    When the user runs \"requirements quick --idea 'Build a REST API'\"\n    29→    Then no question set is generated\n    30→    And the pipeline proceeds directly to draft, review, and seed\n    31→    And the run status is \"completed\"\n    32→    And seed files are written to the run directory\n    33→\n    34→  # RD-004\n    35→  Scenario: Answer submission validates required answers\n    36→    Given a requirements run in \"awaiting_answers\" status\n    37→    When the user runs \"requirements answer <run-id>\"\n    38→    Then the TOML answers file is opened in $EDITOR\n    39→    And answers are validated against the question set\n    40→    And the pipeline resumes from draft, review, and seed"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d6d77a57-6575-434e-8636-d856c1e7216a","uuid":"b91657ca-9885-4837-9fae-4f4ec3a19070","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/conformance/features/requirements_drafting.feature","content":"Feature: Requirements Drafting and Project Seed Handoff\n  The `requirements` command family drives idea-to-seed workflows. Draft mode\n  generates clarifying questions and waits for user answers before proceeding.\n  Quick mode skips questions entirely. Both modes pass through a draft, review,\n  and seed generation pipeline, persisting validated payloads, artifacts, and\n  seed files at durable boundaries.\n\n  # RD-001\n  Scenario: Draft mode generates clarifying questions\n    Given a workspace with an initialized project\n    When the user runs \"requirements draft --idea 'Build a REST API'\"\n    Then a requirements run is created in draft mode\n    And clarifying questions are generated\n    And the run transitions to \"awaiting_answers\" status\n    And an answers.toml template is written to the run directory\n\n  # RD-002\n  Scenario: Draft mode with empty questions skips to completion\n    Given a workspace with an initialized project\n    When the user runs \"requirements draft --idea 'Simple change'\"\n    And the backend returns an empty question set\n    Then the run continues directly through draft, review, and seed\n    And the run status is \"completed\"\n\n  # RD-003\n  Scenario: Quick mode skips questions entirely\n    Given a workspace with an initialized project\n    When the user runs \"requirements quick --idea 'Build a REST API'\"\n    Then no question set is generated\n    And the pipeline proceeds directly to draft, review, and seed\n    And the run status is \"completed\"\n    And seed files are written to the run directory\n\n  # RD-004\n  Scenario: Answer submission validates required answers\n    Given a requirements run in \"awaiting_answers\" status\n    When the user runs \"requirements answer <run-id>\"\n    Then the TOML answers file is opened in $EDITOR\n    And answers are validated against the question set\n    And the pipeline resumes from draft, review, and seed","numLines":40,"startLine":1,"totalLines":267}}}
