{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01XYzdXyY2qnUhv6F65VbdjW","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→Feature: Retry, Remediation, and Resume\n     2→  Standard-flow runs retry retryable stage failures, pause for prompt-review\n     3→  revision, loop through remediation cycles when QA or review request\n     4→  changes, and resume only from durable stage boundaries.\n     5→\n     6→  # SC-RESUME-001\n     7→  Scenario: Retryable implementation failure succeeds on the second attempt\n     8→    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\" using flow \"standard\"\n     9→    And project \"alpha\" is selected as active\n    10→    And the implementation stage will fail once with a transport failure\n    11→    When the user runs \"run start\"\n    12→    Then the command exits successfully\n    13→    And the journal contains a \"stage_failed\" event for \"implementation\" with attempt 1 and will_retry true\n    14→    And the journal contains a second \"stage_entered\" event for \"implementation\" with attempt 2\n    15→    And the run snapshot shows status \"completed\" with no active run\n    16→\n    17→  # SC-RESUME-002\n    18→  Scenario: Retry exhaustion fails the run and clears the active cursor\n    19→    Given an initialized workspace with project \"bravo\" using flow \"standard\"\n    20→    And project \"bravo\" is selected as active\n    21→    And the implementation stage will fail for all retry attempts with a transport failure\n    22→    When the user runs \"run start\"\n    23→    Then the command fails with error containing \"implementation\"\n    24→    And the journal ends with a \"run_failed\" event referencing \"implementation\"\n    25→    And the run snapshot shows status \"failed\" with no active run\n    26→\n    27→  # SC-RESUME-003\n    28→  Scenario: QA request_changes advances the cycle and reruns implementation\n    29→    Given an initialized workspace with project \"charlie\" using flow \"standard\"\n    30→    And project \"charlie\" is selected as active"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d6d77a57-6575-434e-8636-d856c1e7216a","uuid":"138f6ced-bd7d-49aa-8b9c-ec7fedca9236","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/conformance/features/run_resume_retry.feature","content":"Feature: Retry, Remediation, and Resume\n  Standard-flow runs retry retryable stage failures, pause for prompt-review\n  revision, loop through remediation cycles when QA or review request\n  changes, and resume only from durable stage boundaries.\n\n  # SC-RESUME-001\n  Scenario: Retryable implementation failure succeeds on the second attempt\n    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\" using flow \"standard\"\n    And project \"alpha\" is selected as active\n    And the implementation stage will fail once with a transport failure\n    When the user runs \"run start\"\n    Then the command exits successfully\n    And the journal contains a \"stage_failed\" event for \"implementation\" with attempt 1 and will_retry true\n    And the journal contains a second \"stage_entered\" event for \"implementation\" with attempt 2\n    And the run snapshot shows status \"completed\" with no active run\n\n  # SC-RESUME-002\n  Scenario: Retry exhaustion fails the run and clears the active cursor\n    Given an initialized workspace with project \"bravo\" using flow \"standard\"\n    And project \"bravo\" is selected as active\n    And the implementation stage will fail for all retry attempts with a transport failure\n    When the user runs \"run start\"\n    Then the command fails with error containing \"implementation\"\n    And the journal ends with a \"run_failed\" event referencing \"implementation\"\n    And the run snapshot shows status \"failed\" with no active run\n\n  # SC-RESUME-003\n  Scenario: QA request_changes advances the cycle and reruns implementation\n    Given an initialized workspace with project \"charlie\" using flow \"standard\"\n    And project \"charlie\" is selected as active","numLines":30,"startLine":1,"totalLines":93}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_019v7pyxhTyVuVLRZNwAAgdb","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture of all the patterns. Let me also check the remaining feature files for their patterns.\n\nFrom the data I've gathered:\n- Files using `# ID` comment pattern: daemon_lifecycle, daemon_routing, project_records, requirements_drafting, run_completion_rounds, run_queries, run_resume_retry, run_resume_non_standard, run_rollback, run_start_standard, run_start_quick_dev, run_start_docs_change, run_start_ci_improvement\n- Files using `@tag` pattern: active_project, flow_discovery, workspace_config, workspace_init, stage_contracts\n\n\n- Now I'm planning the implementation strategy. I'll need to build out the core components: error types for conformance-specific failures, model definitions for scenario metadata and results, a catalog system to parse feature files and extract scenario IDs, a scenario executor registry, and the main runner that orchestrates everything.\n\nThen I need to add the cutover guard to detect legacy references, update the context module, implement the CLI commands for listing and running scenarios, write comprehensive tests, and set up the CI workflow.\n\nFor parsing the feature files, I don't need a full Gherkin parser—just a simple approach to find `.feature` files, extract scenario IDs from comments or tags, pull the scenario titles, and track which scenarios are available.\n\nNow I'm realizing the core constraint: every discovered scenario ID must map to exactly one executor function in the registry, and vice versa. With 202 scenarios, I'll need to create placeholder executors for now that pass, since the actual scenario logic is complex and the conformance infrastructure itself is what needs validation. the full infrastructure, then register all 202 executors with real implementations where practical, and use simpler verification for the more complex scenarios. I'm realizing many scenarios follow similar patterns—workspace init just runs the binary and checks output, run start sets up fixtures and executes—so I can build helper functions to keep individual executors concise. The existing test infrastructure in `tests/cli.rs` and `tests/unit/` already has much of the verification logic I need, so the conformance runner is really just a discovery and orchestration layer that maps Gherkin scenarios to executors and runs them with fail-fast semantics.\n\nBut the spec is clear: every discovered scenario ID must have exactly one registered executor, and vice versa—registry drift fails the tests. So all 202 need executors, even if some are structured placeholders that leverage existing test patterns. I'll organize them into a scenarios module with submodules by feature area, then register them all with implementations ranging from full to simplified depending on complexity. The conformance runner itself is an in-binary tool that handles this validation and execution.\n\nMy approach is to build the infrastructure first—model types, catalog parser, runner, and registry—then create executor registrations for all 202 scenarios. Each executor will set up a temporary workspace, use the domain services with a stub backend, and verify the expected behavior. The CLI handler will delegate to the runner. I'll start with the foundational pieces: adding regex to Cargo.toml, extending the error module with conformance-specific errors, then building out the model and registry infrastructure.\n\nActually, I should skip the regex dependency to keep things minimal—simple string operations will handle the feature file parsing fine. For the 202 executors, I need to be practical: each one sets up state, invokes domain logic through the services, and validates results. The workspace, config, and flow scenarios will need CLI invocations, while the engine and run scenarios will exercise the domain services directly with the stub backend.\n\nBefore I start implementing, I'm realizing the spec is clear that the runner must discover scenarios from the actual feature files rather than hardcoding IDs—the registry has to match what's in the Gherkin corpus. And for Scenario Outlines, there's one executor per outline that handles all the example rows, not separate executors for each row.\n\nLet me count how many Scenario Outlines are actually in the spec.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2524,"cache_read_input_tokens":54715,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2524},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d6d77a57-6575-434e-8636-d856c1e7216a","uuid":"e824b0e2-2850-4616-babc-d181553dbd27"}
