d, and validating the output—so I can create helper functions that reduce boilerplate and keep individual executor definitions concise.\n\nSince the conformance tests are really just verifying behavior that's already covered in the existing unit and CLI tests, I don't need to make the executors exhaustive. I should focus on a solid registry mechanism, useful helper functions, and lean executors that hit the key points of each scenario. I'll aim for around 5-15 lines per executor and start writing to see how this scales.\n\nThe spec requires isolated temp workspaces, which means CLI scenarios run the binary in a temp directory, while domain-focused scenarios can use the internal APIs directly with a stub backend. Since the runner executes inside the binary, I have access to the workspace governance, project operations, workflow composition, and agent execution modules. For true end-to-end conformance though, I should still consider running the actual binary for some scenarios.\n\nI'm settling on a hybrid approach: simple CLI operations like init and config go through subprocess, while complex engine scenarios like run start and completion rounds use domain services directly. This mirrors the existing test structure where CLI integration tests are separate from unit tests.\n\nNow I need to figure out how to locate the binary when the conformance runner is executing inside it—I can use the current executable path rather than relying on build-time environment variables.\n\nAlright, time to start writing. I'm organizing this into batches: first the core model and error handling updates, then the scenario and runner logic, followed by the CLI conformance module, and finally tests and CI configuration.\n\nActually, let me double-check the scenario count by looking at the feature files more carefully—I want to make sure I'm not overcommitting to 202 executors when the actual breakdown might be smaller. I'm verifying the count: there are 201 individual scenarios plus 1 scena